] movie.\n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.3\n| Title = The Riverbed 5000\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|24}}\n| ShortSummary = King and his group participate on a car race to win $5000 and a kiss from the actress Raquel Wrench.\n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.4\n| Title = Surf's Up\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|1}}\n| ShortSummary = King and his group go to Tempest Beach for a picnic. After Skids works on a customized surfboard, Big H enters its surfing competition.\n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.5\n| Title = The King and His Jokers\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|8}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.6\n| Title = Hot Gold Fever\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|15}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.7\n| Title = The Carnival Caper\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|22}}\n| ShortSummary = At the carnival, King and his group run into Yukayuka's country cousin Elmo. When attempting to free Elmo, Yukayuka is mistaken for his cousin by the carnival's owner Mr. Gridley who also catches King's group. Now King must work to free Elmo from the carnival business for good.\n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.8\n| Title = The Unhappy Heavy Hippo\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|29}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.9\n| Title = The King for Prez\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|5}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.10\n| Title = Snowbound Safari\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|12}}\n| ShortSummary = In the North Woods, King and his group go looking for [[Bigfoot]] who is on a rampage and plan to get the reward for its capture. Though catching this Bigfoot won't be easy for them.\n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.11\n| Title = The Great Billionaire Chase Case\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|19}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.12\n| Title = Boat Fever\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|26}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = H.13\n| Title = Go for It, King\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|12|3}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = B11030\n}}\n|}\n\n===Posse Impossible===\nThe [[Sheriff]] of Saddlesore (voiced by [[Bill Woodson]]) and his hopeless posse of [[cowboy]]s: Stick (voiced by [[Daws Butler]] in a hillbilly voice), Big Duke (voiced by [[Daws Butler]] impersonating [[John Wayne]]) and Blubber (voiced by [[Chuck McCann]]) jail notorious [[Outlaw (stock character)|outlaws]] by outbungling the rascals. In every segment, the Sheriff goes after some no-good polecat which ends with the bad guys behind bars.\n\nA prototype version of the posse was featured in an final episode of ''[[Hong Kong Phooey]]''.\n\n====Episodes====\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#700070; width:30px\"| {{Abbr|N\u00ba|Number}}\n! style=\"background:#700070\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#700070; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.1\n| Title = Big Duke and Li'l Lil\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|10}}\n| ShortSummary = It takes fancy footwork from Duke to rescue a dance-hall girl named Li'l Lil.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.2\n| Title = Trouble at Ghostarado\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|17}}\n| ShortSummary = The Sheriff and the Posse go silver-mining.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.3\n| Title = The Not So Great Train Robbery\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|24}}\n| ShortSummary = The Posse tags some payroll thieves.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.4\n| Title = The Alabama Brahma Bull\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|1}}\n| ShortSummary = A bull rounds up some cattle rustlers!\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.5\n| Title = The Crunch Bunch Crashout\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|8}}\n| ShortSummary = Outlaws outwit the Sheriff and the Posse!\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.6\n| Title = One of Our Rivers Is Missing\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|15}}\n| ShortSummary = The town of Saddlesore is going dry.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.7\n| Title = The Sneakiest Rustler in the West\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|22}}\n| ShortSummary = The Posse disguise themselves as cattle to bully a rustler.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.8\n| Title = Bad Medicine\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|29}}\n| ShortSummary = A snake oil salesman gets a taste of his own medicine.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.9\n| Title = Busting Boomerino\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|5}}\n| ShortSummary = The circus puts on a sideshow at the bank.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.10\n| Title = Roger the Dodger\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|12}}\n| ShortSummary = The Posse tricks a clever crook.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.11\n| Title = Riverboat Sam, the Gambling Man\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|19}}\n| ShortSummary = The Posse puts a casino swindler in dry dock.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.12\n| Title = The Invisible Kid\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|26}}\n| ShortSummary = The Sheriff and the Posse try to catch a criminal sight unseen!\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = P.13\n| Title = Calamity John\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|12|3}}\n| ShortSummary = A bad-luck bank robber brings accidents to the town of Saddlesore.\n| LineColor = 700070\n}}\n|}\n\n===Shake, Rattle & Roll===\nShake (voiced by [[Paul Winchell]]), Rattle (voiced by [[Lennie Weinrib]]), and Roll (voiced by [[Joe E. Ross]]) are three [[ghost]]s who run the Haunted Inn, a [[hotel]] for ghosts and other supernatural creatures as they tend to their needs. Their workplace hijinks are sometimes disrupted by self-proclaimed \"ghost exterminator\" and nemesis Sidney Merciless (voiced by [[Alan Oppenheimer]]) who wants to rid the world of ghosts. They also tend to have problems with the Ghost Mouse as their Poltercat helps in attempts to get rid of it.\n\n====Episodes====\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#0000A0; width:30px\"| {{Abbr|N\u00ba|Number}}\n! style=\"background:#0000A0\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#0000A0; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = S.1\n| Title = Guess What's Coming to Dinner\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|10}}\n| ShortSummary = As Roll works on making breakfast for the guests, he, Shake, and Rattle find a giant egg containing a baby lizard that grows upon eating different things.\n| LineColor = 0000A0\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = S.2\n| Title = The Ghostly Ghoul Is a Ghastling Ghost\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|17}}\n| ShortSummary = \n| LineColor = 0000A0\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = S.3\n| Title = There's No Pest Like a Singing Guest\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|24}}\n| ShortSummary = Shake, Rattle, and Roll have booked the [[Erik (The Phantom of the Opera)|Phantom of the Opera]] as the entertainer of the Haunted Inn. Though him doing his opera singing before the performance is starting to disturb the guests.\n| LineColor = 0000A0\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = S.4\n| Title = Shake the Lion-Hearted\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|1}}\n| ShortSu