. Gridley (in \"The Carnival Caper\"), Newsman (in \"Snowbound Safari\"), Bigfoot/Robber (in \"Snowbound Safari\")\n* [[Alan Oppenheimer]] - Sidney Merciless\n* [[Patricia Parris]] \n* [[Joe E. Ross]] - Roll\n* [[Ken Sansom]] \n* [[Susan Silo]] - Zelda\n* [[Hal Smith (actor)|Hal Smith]] \n* [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]] - Abernathy (in \"The Fright Farm\"), Hunter Hunt (in \"The Blue Kangaroo\")\n* [[Alex Tramunti]] \n* [[Janet Waldo]] \n* [[Lennie Weinrib]] - King, Rattle, Yukayuka, Park Ranger (in \"Snowbound Safari\"), Vampire (in \"There's No Pest Like a Singing Guest\")\n* [[Frank Welker]] - Carnival Worker (in \"The Carnival Caper\"), Ringmaster (in \"The Carnival Caper\")\n* [[Paul Winchell]] - Shake\n* [[Bill Woodson]] - Sheriff of Saddlesore\n\n==Home media==\nAll thirteen episodes of ''Posse Impossible'' were released on [[VHS]] by [[Worldvision Enterprises]] on November 25, 1988.<ref>[http://www.ebay.com/itm/Posse-Impossible-Ricochet-Rabbit-Hanna-Barbera-Vintage-1988-video-trade-ad-/280925581762?_ul=PE Posse Impossible & Ricochet Rabbit videocassettes (1988)]</ref>  In addition, one episode of ''Shake, Rattle & Roll'' was released on VHS as part of a compilation titled ''Scooby-Doo & Friends: Mostly Ghostly'' by Hanna-Barbera Home Video in 1990.\n\n==Other appearances==\n* Undercover Elephant appeared in some episodes of ''[[Yogi's Treasure Hunt]]''.\n* Reruns of ''CB Bears'' and ''Undercover Elephant'' aired in the 1980s run of ''[[Captain Kangaroo]]''.\n* Reruns of ''Undercover Elephant'' were shown as one of the fillers for the adaption of ''[[Wake, Rattle, and Roll]]''.\n* Blast-Off Buzzard and Crazylegs appeared in an episode of ''[[Tom & Jerry Kids]]'' in which they actually talk.\n* Undercover Elephant made a cameo in the \"Agent Penny\" episode of the ''[[Secret Squirrel#Broadcast history|Super Secret Secret Squirrel]]'' segment of ''[[2 Stupid Dogs]]''.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|United States|Animation|Television|Radio}}<!--Radio since the CB bears use CB radio-->\n* {{IMDb title|0075487}}\n* [https://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/A-C/C.B._Bears/ ''CB Bears''] at the [[Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n\n{{Hanna-Barbera}}\n{{Children's programming on NBC in the 1970s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cb Bears}}\n[[Category:1977 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1977 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American children's television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated mystery television series]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:Hanna-Barbera characters]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about bears]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| image                = CB Bears.jpg\n| caption              = Title card\n| genre                = [[Animation]]<br>[[Comedy]]\n| camera               =\n| picture_format       =\n| runtime              = 60 minutes\n| creator              =\n| director             = [[Charles August Nichols|Charles A. Nichols]]\n| executive_producer   = {{Ubl|[[William Hanna]]|[[Joseph Barbera]]}}\n| composer             = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| starring             =\n| voices               = {{ubl|[[Sheldon Allman]]|[[Michael Bell (actor)|Michael Bell]]|[[Daws Butler]]|[[Henry Corden]]|[[Susan Davis (actor)|Susan Davis]]|[[Bob Hastings]]|[[Marvin Kaplan]]|[[Chuck McCann]]|[[Ginny McSwain]]|[[Don Messick]]|[[Alan Oppenheimer]]|[[Joe E. Ross]]|[[Susan Silo]]|[[Lennie Weinrib]]|[[Paul Winchell]]|[[Bill Woodson|William Woodson]]}}\n| narrated             = [[Bill Woodson|William Woodson]] (opening narration)\n| theme_music_composer = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| opentheme            =\n| company              = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]]\n| distributor          = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| endtheme             =\n| country              = USA\n| location             =\n| language             = English\n| network              = [[NBC]]\n| audio_format         = [[Monaural|Mono]]\n| first_aired          = September 10, 1977\n| last_aired           = January 28, 1978\n| num_series           =\n| num_episodes         = 13\n| list_episodes        =\n| preceded_by          =\n| followed_by          =\n| related              =\n| website              =\n}}\n'''''CB Bears''''' is a 60-minute [[Saturday-morning cartoon|Saturday morning animated series]] produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] which aired on [[NBC]] from September 10, 1977 to January 28, 1978.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=117-118 }}</ref> \n\nAs with many Hanna-Barbera shows of the time, ''CB Bears'' was an anthology series with six regular segments: ''The CB Bears'', ''Blast-Off Buzzard'', ''Heyyy, It's the King'', ''Posse Impossible'', ''Shake, Rattle & Roll'' and ''Undercover Elephant''. Each segment riffed on a popular television show or film.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/58/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |pages=58-60}}</ref>\n\nThe ''CB Bears'' segment was a spoof on the 1976 hit show ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', with a trio of ursine investigators given assignments by an unseen dispatcher. Similarly, ''Heyyy, It's the King'' was a takeoff on the 1974 hit ''[[Happy Days]]'', with a royal lion based on [[Henry Winkler|Henry Winkler's]] famous [[Fonzie]]. ''Blast-Off Buzzard'' imitated [[Looney Tunes]]' [[Wile E. Coyote and the Road Runner]], ''Posse Impossible'' was a cowboy show caricaturing [[John Wayne]], ''Shake, Rattle & Roll'' featured a trio of ghosts imitating comics [[Hugh Herbert]], [[Lou Costello]] and [[Marty Allen]], and ''Undercover Elephant'' spoofed ''[[Mission: Impossible (1966 TV series)|Mission: Impossible]]''.<ref name=Woolery/>\n\nOn February 4, 1978, NBC repackaged the show as part of the two-hour ''[[The Go-Go Globetrotters]]'', which also featured reruns of the ''[[Harlem Globetrotters (TV series)|Harlem Globetrotters]]'' series. This lasted until September 3, 1978.<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/76/mode/2up|accessdate=19 March 2020|page=77}}</ref>\n\n==Syndication==\n\nIn syndication, ''CB Bears'' was shown in a shortened half-hour format with ''Blast-Off Buzzard'' and ''Posse Impossible''; ''Heyyy, It's the King!'' was also shown in a shortened half-hour format with ''Shake, Rattle & Roll'' and ''Undercover Elephant''. The show was also rebroadcast on [[Cartoon Network]] from 1995-1997. The ''CB Bears'' theme is also heard in the ending credits of ''[[The Skatebirds]]'' on CBS and ''[[Captain Caveman and the Teen Angels]]'' on ABC.\n\nTitle in French is \"Hure, Lu et Berlu\"\n\n==Segments==\n===The CB Bears===\nHustle (voiced by [[Daws Butler]] impersonating [[Phil Silvers]]), Boogie (voiced by [[Chuck McCann]]) and Bump (voiced by [[Henry Corden]]) are a trio of [[funny animal]] [[bear]] detectives disguised as [[Waste collector|trash collectors]]. They travel the country solving mysteries in a tacky garbage truck called the Perfume Wagon (the CB term for a garbage truck). A sultry-voiced female named Charlie (voiced by [[Susan Davis (actor)|Susan Davis]]) contacts the bears on the truck's [[Citizens' band radio|CB radio]] to give them their assignments. This show was \"inspired\" by the hit TV series ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'' (Bump wore a blonde hairstyle similar to [[Farrah Fawcett]]). Each of the bears' names are based on a 1970s [[disco]] dance, and the show's overall premise made reference to the CB radio craze of the mid-1970s (by this point waning in popularity). Physically and personality-wise, Hustle, Boogie, and Bump resemble Hair Bear, Bubi Bear, and Square Bear, respectively, from ''[[Help!... It's the Hair Bear Bunch!]]''; [[Daws Butler]] provided the same Phil Silvers-esque voice for both Hustle and Hair.\n\n====Episodes====\n{| class=wikitable style=\"width:80%; background:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#FFD700; width:30px\"| {{Abbr|N\u00ba|Number}}\n! style=\"background:#FFD700\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#FFD700; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.1\n| Title = The Missing Mansion Mystery\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|10}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears uncover a missing mansion in the midst of an alligator-infested lagoon.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.2\n| Title = The Doomsday Mine\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|17}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears drive out to End of the Trail, Arizona, where people are turning green and strange lights and sounds are emanating from the deserted Doomsday Mine.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.3\n| Title = Follow that Mountain\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|9|24}}\n| ShortSummary = While investigating the strange case of the disappearing mountains, the CB Bears fall into a cavern and are chased by giant [[gopher]]s created by Dr. Terra.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.4\n| Title = Valley of No Return\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|1}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears go deep into the jungle to discover why the animals are fleeing in terror from the Valley of No Return. They find that an archaeologist named Seeker has driven the animals out of the Valley of No Return in order to excavate its lost city.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.5\n| Title = The Fright Farm\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|8}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears follow a mysterious old man named Abernathy who has been stealing animals from the zoo to his hideout at the Fright Farm where he is loading them onto a huge ark.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.6\n| Title = Drackenstein's Revenge\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|15}}\n| ShortSummary = While looking for clues to why all the peasants of Drackenstein are asleep, the CB Bears discover the town's valuables are missing.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.7\n| Title = Water, Water...Nowhere\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|22}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears try to save the world from embittered old ex-sea Captain Sly, who turns water to sand with a machine.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.8\n| Title = The Wild, Wild Wilderness\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|10|29}}\n| ShortSummary = While Charlie warns the CB Bears to watch for strange creatures near their campground, Boogie is snatched up by a giant vine.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.9\n| Title = Island of Terror\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|5}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears battle a [[Enteroctopus|giant octopus]] to reach the sinking island of Mikimos.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.10\n| Title = Go North, Young Bears\n| OriginalAirDate = {{start date|1977|11|12}}\n| ShortSummary = The CB Bears go to the North Pole to search for the source of mysterious floods in the Northwest.\n| LineColor = FFD700\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = C.11\n| Title = The Invasion of the Blobs\n| Origin